  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for differences between long-term and short-term cover crop use in Mediterranean agricultural systems is limited but shows some distinct outcomes. In arable fields, one study from Spain found higher soil quality in plots with long-term cover crops compared to short-term (Action 1345). For water outcomes, one study from Spain found more water in soils with long-term cover crops compared to short-term in some comparisons (Action 1357). In orchards and vineyards, one study from France found more organic matter in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in one of three comparisons (Action 1367). The same French study found more phosphorus in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in one of three comparisons (Action 1367). For soil organisms, one study from France found more microbial biomass in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in some comparisons (Action 1367), and more nematodes in soils with permanent ground cover compared to temporary ground cover in one of three comparisons (Action 1367). For soil erosion, one study from Italy found the least erosion with permanent cover crops and the most erosion with temporary cover crops (Action 1367).",
