  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from Mediterranean regions shows that tillage practices have significant effects on weed populations in arable fields. Seven replicated, randomized, controlled studies from Italy, Lebanon, Spain, and Turkey found more weeds in plots with reduced tillage compared to conventional tillage in some or all comparisons (Action 1399). One study from Italy also found fewer weeds in plots with reduced tillage compared to conventional tillage in some comparisons, while another Italian study found similar numbers of weeds between reduced and conventional tillage (Action 1399). For no-tillage practices, three replicated, controlled studies from Italy and Spain found more weeds in plots with no tillage compared to conventional tillage in some comparisons (Action 1397). Four replicated, controlled studies from Italy, Spain, and the USA found inconsistent differences in weeds between no tillage and conventional tillage systems, with sometimes more weeds in no-tillage plots and sometimes fewer (Action 1397). When comparing no tillage to reduced tillage, four replicated, controlled studies from Italy, Lebanon, and Spain found fewer weeds in plots with no tillage compared to reduced tillage in some or all comparisons (Action 1398). Regarding weed species diversity, two replicated, randomized, controlled studies from Spain and Turkey found similar numbers of weed species in plots with reduced tillage or conventional tillage (Action 1399), while three replicated, controlled studies from Italy and Spain found similar numbers of weed species in plots with or without tillage (Action 1397). One Italian study found more weed species in plots with no tillage compared to conventional tillage (Action 1397).",
