{
  "action_id": "720",
  "action_title": "Allow natural regeneration of ground cover beneath perennial crops",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nNatural enemies on crop trees and vines: Five studies (including one replicated, randomised, controlled test) from Australia, China, Italy and Portugal compared natural and bare ground covers by measuring numbers of natural enemies in fruit tree or vine canopies. Three found effects varied between groups of natural enemies, two found no difference. Two studies from Australia and France compared natural to sown ground cover and found no effect on enemies in crop canopies. Natural enemies on the ground: Five studies (including three replicated, randomised, controlled trials) from Australia, Canada, China, France, and Spain compared natural and bare ground covers by measuring natural enemies on the ground. Two studies found more natural enemies in natural ground cover, but in one the effects were only short-term for most natural enemy groups. Three studies found mixed effects, with higher numbers of some natural enemy groups but not others. Two studies compared natural and sown ground covers, one study found more natural enemies and one found no effect. Pests and crop damage: Four studies (three controlled, one also replicated and randomised) from Italy, Australia and China measured pests and crop damage in regenerated and bare ground covers. Two studies found fewer pests, whilst two studies found effects on pests and crop damage varied for different pest or disease groups. One study found more pests in natural than in sown ground covers.\nCrops studied were apple, grape, lemon, olive and pear."
}

{
  "action_id": "722",
  "action_title": "Grow plants that compete with damaging weeds",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nWeed weight and cover: Nine studies from Australia, Slovakia, the UK and the USA tested the effects of planting species to compete with weeds. All (including four replicated, randomised, controlled trials) found reduced weed plant weight or ground cover, although two found this only in some years or conditions. Weed reproduction and survival: Five studies (including three replicated, randomised, controlled trials) also found that competition reduced weed reproduction, survival or both. One of these found an effect only in one year only.\nCrops studied were clovers, fescues, ryegrass, other grasses and turnip."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query": "What are the documented benefits and drawbacks for pest regulation when planting or maintaining ground cover in Mediterranean orchards and vineyards?", "summary": "Based on studies from Mediterranean orchards and vineyards, planting or maintaining ground cover for pest regulation shows mixed benefits and drawbacks. Benefits include: increased natural enemy numbers in some comparisons, with four replicated, controlled studies from Spain and the USA finding more natural enemies in plots with ground cover compared to plots without ground cover (Action 1395). One study found more natural enemies in plots with mown cover crops one week after mowing compared to before mowing (Action 1395). Studies show potential for increased parasitism of leafhopper eggs, though effects were inconsistent across different comparisons (Action 1395).

However, significant drawbacks were documented: one replicated, randomized, controlled study from the USA found that more grapes were damaged by pests in plots with cover crops compared to bare fallows in some comparisons (Action 1395). For specific pest species, studies found inconsistent effects on leafhopper numbers, with some studies showing fewer leafhoppers in plots with cover crops while others found more leafhoppers or similar numbers (Action 1395). One study found more navel orangeworm moths in plots with resident vegetation compared to tilled soil in one of two comparisons (Action 1395). Additionally, competition effects were noted, with some studies finding more weeds in plots with cover crops compared to bare soil (Action 1395).

Natural regeneration studies showed that effects varied between natural enemy groups, with some studies finding mixed effects where higher numbers of some natural enemy groups occurred but not others, and some studies found more pests in natural ground covers compared to sown ground covers (Action 720). Implementation approaches matter, as studies found fewer pests in plots with mown ground cover compared to unmown ground cover (Action 1395).", "action_ids": ["1395","720"]}

