{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the impacts of restoring habitat along watercourses on different biodiversity groups on Mediterranean farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, restoring habitat along watercourses shows mixed results for different biodiversity groups, with limited specific data from Mediterranean farmland contexts.\n\nFor birds, two replicated site comparisons from Spain found similar numbers of bird species in restored and remnant sites (action 1416). One replicated site comparison from Spain found similar numbers of birds and bird species in restored contaminated sites and uncontaminated sites (action 1416). However, evidence from other regions shows that bird populations increased with the area of restored habitat in the landscape in some comparisons, and implementation studies found more birds or bird species in older restored plots compared to younger restored plots (action 1416).\n\nFor plant communities, studies show that restored sites generally had lower plant cover compared to remnant sites, with some studies finding higher cover of exotic plants (action 1416). Two replicated studies found fewer native plant species in restored forests compared to remnant forests, with one study finding more exotic species (action 1416). However, one study found more plant species in restored sites compared to remnant sites (action 1416).\n\nFor other biodiversity groups, one replicated site comparison found similar numbers of amphibian species, mammal species, and reptile species in restored and remnant sites (action 1416). For invertebrates, evidence shows fewer native ants but similar numbers of invasive ants in restored sites compared to remnant sites, and similar numbers of freshwater invertebrates in restored and reference sites after restoration (action 1416). Pollinator studies found similar numbers of bees and bee species, but different bee communities, in restored and remnant sites (action 1408).\n\nRegarding buffer strips alongside watercourses, three studies from the Netherlands and UK reported positive influence on plant, invertebrate and bird diversity or abundance (action 120). However, two studies from France and Ireland found that riparian buffer strips did not result in an increase in plant species numbers compared to farms without buffer strips (action 120).",
